White takes advantage of black's weak 11th move and gains two pluses 
1. relieves a cramped position
2. creates a lasting weakness in black's position

As a general rule if you are suffering from a cramped game aim to trade peices. This achieves two things for you
1. you create lines and open up squares for your remaining peices
2. you elimenate the attacking peices from your opponent
This is an interesting idea that makes the most out black's trouble. I think black will regret the double pawns in the end game though

It is at this point where white starts to get his legs underneath him. When you have the opportunity to create a pawn weakness in your enemies position do it! The creation of a pawn weakness is encouraged under certian cases. Here is some questions to ask yourself if you are thinking about creating a pawn weakness. 

1. Do you get equivalent compensation?(In this game, I trade a bishop for knight so YES)
2. Do you achieve a strong attack? (In this game, I limit black's attack acheive solid attacking chances with Ne4)
